The Hiyangthang Lairembi Temple (Meitei: ÍØçÍØ§ÍØåÍØ•ÍØ°ÍØäÍØ•ÍØ° ÍØÇÍØ•ÍØ¢ÍØîÍØ¶ÍØùÍØïÍØ§ ÍØÇÍØ•ÍØ¢ÍØÅÍØ™, Old Manipuri: ÍØçÍØ§ÍØåÍØ•ÍØ°ÍØäÍØ•ÍØ° ÍØÇÍØ•ÍØ¢ÍØÇÍØ¶ÍØùÍØÑÍØ§ ÍØÇÍØ•ÍØ¢ÍØÅÍØ™, romanized: hee-yaang-thaang laai-lem-pee laai-shang) is an ancient temple of Goddess Hiyangthang Lairembi (also known as Irai Leima) of Meitei religion (Sanamahism).

The sacred building is situated on the hilltop of Heibok Ching in the Hiyangthang, Manipur.[1][2][3][4] Thousands of devotees thronged at the holy site during the festival time of Lai Haraoba of Sanamahism as well as Durga Puja of Hinduism.[The worship of Goddess Hiyangthang Lairembi (alias Irai Leima) was started by the reign of King Senbi Kiyamba (1467-1508 AD) in Manipur. Right from his era, Sarangthem family members hold grand feasts (Chaklen Katpa) every year in honor of the goddess.

In the 18th century AD, during the reign of King Garib Niwaj (alias Pamheiba), Goddess Hiyangthang Lairembi (alias Irai Leima) was converted to Hindu goddess Kamakhya (a form of Durga). The 3rd day of Durga Puja is celebrated as the "Bor Numit" (literally, Boon Day) in the temple.

On the 22nd of March, 1979, an association was formed to worship Hiyangthang Lairembi (Ireima), the traditional goddess.

I saw a hand-written letter by Netaji which is barely attached to the board. Documents of such National Importance should be FRAMED and preserved better. The content of the same letter should be printed and placed next to it, for the tourists to read it better.

Some of the glasses are very dirty and had stains on them. Needless to say these should be spotless for people to clearly see.

Museum has great potential and all the items curated are important, but if only presented more aptly!

The area outside the museum could be well kept and turned into a park for people to sit down and enjoy. There's a river which has now become a drain and smelling horrible.

Someone should step up and turn this place beautiful with plants, benches, and a river with the famous manipuri water lilies!!!

No pictures of the museum because photography was prohibited.
